VALUES
(42, 20, 13, 24, 36, 3, 3, 'I will send my beloved son', 'Connection of Sending and Hearing', 'This connection highlights the theme of sending a beloved figure to elicit a response from the people. In both passages, there is an expectation that the recipients will respond positively to the one sent, whether it be the beloved son or the message of impending judgment.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 13, 23, 5, 4, 4, NULL, 'Vineyard Imagery and Rejection', 'Both passages emphasize the vineyard as a metaphor for God''s expectations. In Luke, the sending of the beloved son reflects the hope for reverence, while Isaiah questions the failure of the vineyard to produce good fruit.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 13, 28, 6, 4, 4, 'What shall I do?', 'Divine Concern for Rejection', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine frustration with human unfaithfulness. Both passages express a sense of lament and inquiry regarding the people''s response to God''s messengers.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 13, 28, 11, 8, 8, 'my beloved son', 'Divine Compassion and Sending', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of a beloved figure being sent by God, reflecting divine compassion. In Luke, the beloved son is sent in hopes of reverence, while in Hosea, God''s heart is turned towards Israel, expressing deep emotional turmoil over their fate.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 13, 40, 17, 5, 5, 'my beloved son', 'Connection of Beloved Son', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of the ''beloved Son.'' In Luke, the lord of the vineyard sends his beloved son, while in Matthew, God declares Jesus as his beloved Son, highlighting the significance of this title.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 14, 45, 8, 17, 17, 'the inheritance may be ours', 'Heirs and Inheritance Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of inheritance in both passages. In Luke, the husbandmen desire the inheritance by killing the heir, while Romans speaks of being heirs of God and joint-heirs with Christ.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 14, 58, 1, 2, 2, 'This is the heir: come, let us kill him', 'Heirship and Rejection Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of heirship and rejection. In Luke 20:14, the husbandmen plot to kill the heir, while Hebrews 1:2 affirms that the Son is appointed heir of all things.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 14, 1, 37, 18, 20, 'let us kill him', 'Conspiracy Against the Heir', 'This connection highlights the theme of conspiracy against a favored son. Both passages depict individuals plotting to kill someone they perceive as a threat to their inheritance or dreams.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 14, 19, 2, 1, 6, 'this is the heir: come, let us kill him', 'Rejection of the Heir', 'Both passages emphasize the rebellion against God''s authority and His anointed. In Luke, the husbandmen plot to kill the heir, paralleling the rulers'' counsel against the Lord in Psalms.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 14, 19, 2, 8, 8, 'the inheritance may be ours', 'Inheritance and Rejection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of inheritance. In Luke 20:14, the husbandmen desire to claim the inheritance by rejecting the heir, while Psalms 2:8 speaks of the inheritance given to the one who asks, highlighting a contrast between rightful claim and usurpation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 14, 40, 2, 2, 16, 'let us kill him', 'Connection of Rejection and Threat', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of rejection of a rightful heir. In Luke, the husbandmen plot to kill the heir, while in Matthew, Herod seeks to destroy the young child, viewing him as a threat to his rule.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 14, 40, 16, 7, 7, 'reasoned among themselves', 'Reasoning Among Themselves', 'Both passages emphasize the act of reasoning among individuals. In Luke, the husbandmen plot against the heir, while in Matthew, the disciples discuss their lack of bread.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 15, 58, 13, 12, 12, 'killed him', 'Rejection and Suffering of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection, as both passages depict the suffering and death of Jesus. In Luke, he is cast out and killed, while Hebrews emphasizes his suffering outside the gate to sanctify the people.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 15, 40, 21, 37, 40, 'cast him out of the vineyard, and killed him', 'Connection of Vineyard Parables', 'Both passages emphasize the act of casting out and killing the son, highlighting the rejection of the heir. They pose a similar question about the lord''s response to the husbandmen''s actions, reinforcing the theme of judgment.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 15, 41, 12, 6, 9, NULL, 'Connection of Vineyard Parables', 'Both passages emphasize the act of killing the son and the subsequent judgment of the lord of the vineyard. This connection highlights the consequences faced by the husbandmen for their actions against the son.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 16, 42, 19, 27, 27, NULL, 'Judgment of Enemies', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment against those who reject authority. Both passages emphasize the consequences for those who oppose the rightful reign, culminating in destruction and punishment.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 16, 40, 21, 41, 41, 'destroy these husbandmen', 'Destruction of Wicked Husbandmen', 'Both passages emphasize the destruction of wicked husbandmen and the transfer of the vineyard to others. This connection highlights the consequences faced by those who fail to produce the expected fruits.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 16, 44, 13, 46, 46, 'give the vineyard to others', 'Rejection of God''s Message', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejecting God''s message. In Luke, the husbandmen''s destruction and the vineyard being given to others parallels Paul''s declaration of turning to the Gentiles after the Jews rejected the word of God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 16, 16, 9, 36, 37, 'give the vineyard to others', 'Servanthood and Dominion', 'This connection highlights the theme of servanthood and the consequences of sin. In both passages, the people acknowledge their subservience and the loss of control over their circumstances due to their actions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 16, 19, 2, 8, 9, 'give the vineyard to others', 'Judgment and Inheritance Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment against unfaithful stewards and the transfer of inheritance. Both passages emphasize the idea of authority being taken away from one group and given to another, with the vineyard representing God''s people and the heathen as a new inheritance.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 16, 19, 21, 8, 10, 'destroy these husbandmen', 'Judgment on Enemies', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine judgment against those who oppose God. Both passages emphasize the destruction of enemies and the removal of their legacy from the earth.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 16, 40, 22, 7, 7, 'destroy these husbandmen', 'Destruction of the Wicked', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine judgment against those who reject God''s messengers. Both passages depict a king or lord who responds with wrath, destroying those who have wronged him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 17, 19, 118, 22, 22, 'The stone which the builders rejected', 'Connection of Rejected Stone', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of a rejected stone becoming the cornerstone. This connection highlights the significance of the stone''s transformation from rejection to prominence.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 17, 23, 28, 16, 16, 'The stone which the builders rejected', 'Cornerstone Rejection Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of the cornerstone, highlighting its rejection by builders in Luke and its establishment as a foundation in Isaiah. This connection underscores the theme of a foundational stone that is both precious and pivotal.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 17, 44, 4, 11, 11, 'The stone which the builders rejected', 'Connection of Rejected Stone', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of the rejected stone becoming the cornerstone. The phrase ''the stone which the builders rejected'' appears in both, linking their messages.', 'quotation', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 17, 40, 21, 42, 42, 'the stone which the builders rejected', 'Connection of Rejected Stone', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase, ''the stone which the builders rejected,'' highlighting its significance in scripture. This connection illustrates the theme of rejection leading to exaltation.', 'quotation', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 17, 41, 12, 10, 10, 'The stone which the builders rejected', 'Connection of Rejected Stone', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase ''the stone which the builders rejected'' and its significance as becoming ''the head of the corner.'' This connection highlights the continuity in the message regarding the rejected stone''s ultimate importance.', 'quotation', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 20, 17, 60, 2, 7, 8, 'the stone which the builders rejected', 'Connection of Rejected Stone', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of the ''stone which the builders rejected.'' This connection highlights how this rejected stone becomes significant, serving as the ''head of the corner'' and a ''stone of stumbling'' for the disobedient.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
